description.text:
### Tested versions

Godot 4.4.1

### System information

Godot 4.4.1, Mobile Renderer, Microsoft Windows 11 Pro Version 10.0.26100 Build 26100

### Issue description

The documentation section [GUI Skinning: Customizing a Project](https://docs.godotengine.org/en/stable/tutorials/ui/gui_skinning.html#customizing-a-project) indicates that themes are supposed to be searched "using control's type variation, class name and parent class names". However, it only returns the correct result when I explicitly pass in the class name.

```csharp
GetThemeFont(nameof(font), nameof(MusicDisplay)); // returns correct result (project-scope theme, type-specific)

GetThemeFont(nameof(font)); // returns default font (incorrect)
```

Furthermore, theme overrides are ignored unless `null` is passed in as the class name.

```csharp
AddThemeFontOverride(nameof(font), value); // set override

GetThemeFont(nameof(font), nameof(MusicDisplay)); // does NOT return the override (incorrect)

GetThemeFont(nameof(font)); // returns the override (correct)
```

This leads to a rediculous situation where I have to pollute my eyes with this bogus monstrosity:

```csharp
// ternary workaround: correctly gets value from override, ancestor, or project theme
GetThemeFont(nameof(font), HasThemeFontOverride(nameof(font)) ? null : nameof(MusicDisplay));
```

This bug causes two headaches:
1. I shouldn't have to explicitly check `HasThemeFontOverride()`. The `GetTheme*` methods are responsible for checking that.
2. The documentation states that a control's class name should automatically be used during the search.

```csharp
// this line is supposed to do everything
GetThemeFont(nameof(font));
```

### Steps to reproduce

I included a helpful demonstration if you open the included sample [ThemeBug.zip](https://github.com/user-attachments/files/20370156/ThemeBug.zip)

![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/fed34741-9ea2-4a48-965a-a0a7fd2f45bb)

There are two `MusicDisplay` items in `Main.tscn`. If you run the project, `DisplayLeft` is inheriting its theme from the project theme, and `DisplayRight` is inheriting its theme from the node `AncestorWithTheme`. This works because the class name is explicitly passed to the `GetTheme*` functions:

```csharp
font = GetThemeFont(nameof(font), nameof(MusicDisplay));
font_size = GetThemeFontSize(nameof(font_size), nameof(MusicDisplay));
color = GetThemeColor(nameof(color), nameof(MusicDisplay));
```

Now try disabling the `FetchByClass` export on either of them. You'll notice that the `GetTheme*` methods are falling back to `ThemeDB.GetDefaultTheme()`. That's because the optional parameter is empty:

```csharp
font = GetThemeFont(nameof(font));
font_size = GetThemeFontSize(nameof(font_size));
color = GetThemeColor(nameof(color));
```

The documentation says that it's supposed to search using the class name automatically, but it doesn't. If that's not strange enough, try setting theme overrides. You get the exact mirror of the issue; specifying a class name will cause it to skip over the theme override that was set with `AddTheme*Override()`. You have to pass `null` to fetch the override.

### Minimal reproduction project (MRP)

[ThemeBug.zip](https://github.com/user-attachments/files/20370156/ThemeBug.zip)

<details><summary>MusicDisplay.cs</summary>

```csharp
using Godot;
using System;
using System.Linq;

public partial class MusicDisplay : Control
{
    public const string TEST_MESSAGE = "The shadows lengthen in Carcosa.";

    private bool fetchByClass = true;
    [Export]
    public bool FetchByClass
    {
        get => fetchByClass;
        set
        {
            fetchByClass = value;
            EmitSignalThemeChanged();
        }
    }

    private Font font;
    [Export][ExportGroup("Theme Overrides")]
    public Font Font
    {
        get => font;
        set
        {
            // add and remove pop OnThemeChanged()
            if (HasThemeFontOverride(nameof(font)) && value is null) RemoveThemeFontOverride(nameof(font));
            else AddThemeFontOverride(nameof(font), value);
        }
    }

    private int font_size;
    [Export][ExportGroup("Theme Overrides")]
    public int FontSize
    {
        get => font_size;
        set
        {
            // add and remove pop OnThemeChanged()
            if (HasThemeFontSizeOverride(nameof(font_size)) && value == default) RemoveThemeFontSizeOverride(nameof(font_size));
            else AddThemeFontSizeOverride(nameof(font_size), value);
        }
    }

    private Color color;
    [Export][ExportGroup("Theme Overrides")]
    public Color Color
    {
        get => color;
        set
        {
            // add and remove pop OnThemeChanged()
            if (HasThemeColorOverride(nameof(color)) && value == default) RemoveThemeColorOverride(nameof(color));
            else AddThemeColorOverride(nameof(color), value);
        }
    }

    public MusicDisplay()
    {
        ThemeChanged += OnThemeChanged;
    }

    private int calls;
    private void OnThemeChanged()
    {
        GD.Print($"OnThemeChanged pop {++calls}");

        if (FetchByClass)
        {
            /* 
                ----------
                This does theme traversal, but fails at the override. 
            */
            font = GetThemeFont(nameof(font), nameof(MusicDisplay));
            font_size = GetThemeFontSize(nameof(font_size), nameof(MusicDisplay));
            color = GetThemeColor(nameof(color), nameof(MusicDisplay));
        }
        else
        {
            /*  ----------
                This gets the override, but fails at theme traversal. 
            */
            font = GetThemeFont(nameof(font));
            font_size = GetThemeFontSize(nameof(font_size));
            color = GetThemeColor(nameof(color));
        }

        QueueRedraw();
    }

    public override void _Draw()
    {
        DrawRect(new Rect2(Vector2.Zero, Size), Color);

        var strSize = Font.GetStringSize(TEST_MESSAGE, fontSize: font_size);
        var tloc = new Vector2(Size.X / 2 - strSize.X / 2, Size.Y / 2);

        DrawString(Font, tloc, TEST_MESSAGE, HorizontalAlignment.Center, fontSize: font_size, modulate: Color.Inverted());

        DrawSetTransform(Size, (float)Math.PI); // upside-down
        var mirror = new string(TEST_MESSAGE.Reverse().ToArray()); // backwards

        tloc = tloc with { Y = tloc.Y - strSize.Y };
        DrawString(Font, tloc, mirror, HorizontalAlignment.Center, fontSize: font_size, modulate: Color.Inverted());

        // TODO: as a separate bug, I was unable to use the "direction" property of DrawString()
        //       to create a proper mirror image. instead, I decided to reverse the text which
        //       makes the letters backwards instead of looking like a proper reflection.

        // TODO: Color.Inverted() doesn't look the way I expected. I haven't investigated whether
        //       this is another bug, of if that's how it's supposed to look.
    }
}
```

</details>

### Tested versions

Reproducible in:
v4.4.1.stable.official [49a5bc7b6]
v4.5.dev3.official [55fc6e73f]

### System information

Godot v4.4.1.stable - Windows 11 (build 22621) - Multi-window, 1 monitor - Vulkan (Forward+) - dedicated NVIDIA GeForce RTX 4060 Laptop GPU (NVIDIA; 31.0.15.3713) - 13th Gen Intel(R) Core(TM) i7-13620H (16 threads)

### Issue description

Unlike AudioEffectAmplify, the panning is not interpolated over the frame, which makes crackle when it changes

### Steps to reproduce

Change the panning of an AudioEffectPanner of an active bus, also works in editor

Solution is very simple:


In audio_effect_panner.cpp change

```
void AudioEffectPannerInstance::process(const AudioFrame *p_src_frames, AudioFrame *p_dst_frames, int p_frame_count) {
	float lvol = CLAMP(1.0 - base->pan, 0, 1);
	float rvol = CLAMP(1.0 + base->pan, 0, 1);

	for (int i = 0; i < p_frame_count; i++) {
		p_dst_frames[i].left = p_src_frames[i].left * lvol + p_src_frames[i].right * (1.0 - rvol);
		p_dst_frames[i].right = p_src_frames[i].right * rvol + p_src_frames[i].left * (1.0 - lvol);
	}
}
```
to
```
void AudioEffectPannerInstance::process(const AudioFrame *p_src_frames, AudioFrame *p_dst_frames, int p_frame_count) {

    float pan = base->pan;
    float p = mix_pan;
    float pan_inc = (pan - mix_pan) / float(p_frame_count);

    for (int i = 0; i < p_frame_count; i++) {
        float lvol = CLAMP(1.0 - p, 0, 1);
        float rvol = CLAMP(1.0 + p, 0, 1);
		p_dst_frames[i].left = p_src_frames[i].left * lvol + p_src_frames[i].right * (1.0 - rvol);
		p_dst_frames[i].right = p_src_frames[i].right * rvol + p_src_frames[i].left * (1.0 - lvol);
        p += pan_inc;
    }
    mix_pan = base->pan;
}
```
and in audio_effect_panner.h at AudioEffectPannerInstance add

`float mix_pan;`

